## Code Style Rules

- Python 3.11+ syntax
- Use `@dataclass` for all data models (`PageRecord`, `SearchResult`)
- Type hints on every function signature
- Constants in ALL_CAPS in `config.py` only — never hardcoded inline
- Max line length: 88 characters (Black-compatible)
- Docstrings on every class and public method (one-line is fine)
- Use f-strings, not `.format()` or `%`

---

## Architecture Rules

Follow this exact module responsibility split:

| File | Owns | Does NOT own |
|---|---|---|
| `core/config.py` | Constants | Any logic |
| `core/index.py` | Shared state + lock | HTTP, threading setup |
| `core/crawler.py` | Fetch + parse + enqueue | Index lock internals |
| `core/searcher.py` | Scoring logic | Threading, I/O |
| `core/dashboard.py` | Terminal display | Business logic |
| `core/api.py` | Flask + SSE + HTTP routes | Crawler internals |
| `main.py` | Wiring + thread lifecycle | Business logic |

---

## Concurrency Rules

- Back-pressure MUST be implemented via `queue.Queue(maxsize=QUEUE_MAX_SIZE)`
  Workers call `url_queue.put(item)` — this blocks naturally when full. Do not
  implement a custom throttle on top of this unless also adding `REQUEST_DELAY_SEC`.
- All worker threads MUST be started as `daemon=False` except the dashboard thread
  which MUST be `daemon=True`.
- Use `threading.Lock` (not `RLock`) unless recursive locking is explicitly needed.
- `mark_visited()` in `CrawlIndex` MUST be atomic: check + add in one lock block.

---

## Crawling Rules

- URL normalization order: urljoin → strip fragment → lowercase scheme+host → domain filter
- Respect `SAME_DOMAIN_ONLY` from config — never crawl outside the seed domain unless
  this flag is False
- Respect `MAX_DEPTH` — never enqueue a URL at depth > MAX_DEPTH
- Each worker MUST sleep `REQUEST_DELAY_SEC` between requests (be polite)
- Timeout every HTTP request using `urllib.request.urlopen(url, timeout=REQUEST_TIMEOUT_SEC)`

---

## Search / Scoring Rules

- `searcher.search()` is a pure function — no side effects, no global state
- Relevance score formula:
  `score = keyword_freq_sum + (2 * title_keyword_matches)`
- Return only results with `score > 0`
- Results sorted descending by score
- Return as list of `SearchResult` dataclass instances

